    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1319325978" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1319325978" />
    <a title="Annie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/38036772-annie"><img alt="Annie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1586205974p2/38036772.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1319325978?book_show_action=true">Aug 15, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Annie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Annie" href="/user/show/38036772-annie">Annie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1319325978" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16930817638146707762">Dear <i>God</i>, that was depressing. Soul-crushingly depressing. <br/><br/>But considering this is a book about the end of the world, there’s no sense of urgency. There’s just this sense of complacency among most of the characters that drives me crazy. Captain Towers’s philosophy is a good example: <i>“You just can’t dodge it. You’ve got to take what’s coming to you, and make the best of it. We’ve just got to take it.”</i> <br/><br/>Towers (and the author, clearly) gets frustrated with Moira, my favourite character, because he </span>
  <span id="freeText16930817638146707762" style="display:none">Dear <i>God</i>, that was depressing. Soul-crushingly depressing. <br /><br />But considering this is a book about the end of the world, there’s no sense of urgency. There’s just this sense of complacency among most of the characters that drives me crazy. Captain Towers’s philosophy is a good example: <i>“You just can’t dodge it. You’ve got to take what’s coming to you, and make the best of it. We’ve just got to take it.”</i> <br /><br />Towers (and the author, clearly) gets frustrated with Moira, my favourite character, because he thinks it’s pointless to drink as much as she does. <br /><br />She drinks literally nonstop. Refuses to do anything until someone buys her a drink first. “Never a dull moment,” as the characters repeatedly say of Moira. <br /><br />Towers seems to think this is a waste of time, and thinks she should do things like learn a new skill with the 6 months they have left, or find a job. <br /><br />But what’s the point of working if you’re going to die soon, and everyone else is going to die soon, so that no work you do will have any impact at all? How is that less pointless than drinking and partying all day? <br /><br />Ditto Towers’s own occupation: taking a submarine around different places to see which places are “out” (i.e. everyone is dead) and which places are not yet. What’s the point of that? They all will be soon. Towers says: <i>“It’s fun just finding out. Some games are fun even when you lose. Even when you know you’re going to lose before you start. It’s fun just playing them.”</i> <br /><br />No, it’s not fun figuring out who’s dead and who will be soon. You know what’s fun? Drinking. Stop pretending your way of coping with death is superior to Moira’s. Who gives a fuck what she does with the months left? You’re not helping people any more than she is. <br /><br />He’s not the only man in this book who condescends to women characters—who, naturally, are all written as naive and irrational, while the men are brave, stalwart, sensible. Peter Holmes thinks about his wife: <br /><br /><i>“These bloody women, sheltered from realities, living in a sentimental dream world of their own! If they’d face up to things they could help a man, help him enormously. While they clung to the dream world they were just a bloody millstone round his neck.”</i> LOL I’m glad you’re about to die of radiation poisoning, you schmuck. <br /><br />[And no, I don’t need to accept it “because of the times in which it was written.” I can take some mildly antiquated views, but nothing this blatant. Not when Shute has plenty of contemporaries who aren’t blatantly misogynistic.]<br /><br />2 stars because it was well-written and thoughtful. No more stars, because the men in this book (and the author) are condescending to the women characters. And also because everyone is so damn complacent and I’m not here for it. </span>
  <a data-text-id="16930817638146707762" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


